postcontent:
I have for sale the badass Socom 16 M1A from Springfield Armory. If you know your rifles you'll know what this one is. This is a rugged power house. Why lug around the really big and heavy M1As or FALs when you can slam .308 down range with this compact monster? It's an M14/M1A, but in a smaller package that makes it great for hunting/woods walking. I've never experienced a failure to fire or any other issue with this rifle. When I've seen more expensive .308's hiccup this baby cycles any type of .308 round like a champ and slings it with some amazing accuracy. There is also a front rail for mounting scout type optics. The barrel is outfitted with SA's muzzle brake that tames the recoil, when you pull the trigger this gun thunders. 

I am the first owner of this rifle and have had it for only two years. I have taken great care of this thing. There are no blemishes or scratches on the rifle. There are some brass marks on the charging handle near the ejection port, this is normal wear. I have always put a light coat of oil/solvent on this thing and babied it after every range trip. The barrel always was swabbed out and treated. This machine has been taken care of and will last longer than all of us. It will not fail you. You cannot break this thing. Why dink around with polymer wonder snowflake guns when you could throw this thing off a building and it'll keep slinging lead like nothing happened to it?

title: For Sale:  Antique Turkish Mauser Model 88/05/35 - 8mm Mauser Caliber NICE
postcontent:
I took this rifle in trade a while back because of its overall good condition and it's antique status. However I've decided to sell it in order to pursue something a little closer to my true interests.   

It's a Turkish Model 88/05/35 long rifle chambered in 8x57 caliber (8mm Mauser). It was born as a German 1888 Commission Rifle that later went through the 1905 conversion to the 8x57 round. Then sometime between about 1916 and 1918 the Germans sold many of them to Turks who then modified them further in the 1930's and early 1940's with the final result illustrated in the rifle for sale here.   

It's in good to very good condition for it's age with about 75% - 80% of its original finish. There is no pitting on any of the metal surfaces and the wood looks good as well with no cracks or repairs. It's fully functional and actually shoots well. Perhaps the best feature is the bore which is in excellent shape. Rifling is strong and there isn't a bit of rust or darkness. In fact it's actually quite shiny. It's unusual to find a Turk rifle of this vintage with a bright and shiny bore since the ammo they used was very corrosive.   

These rifles were built then underwent two major overhauls so virtually none of them have all matching numbers. In this case the receiver numbers match all the numbers on the sights which is just about as good as it gets. Then the bolt is numbered in Turkish/Arabic which I don't read. So I'm not really sure if it's numberd to match the receiver or not. 

Rifle comes with what appears to be the correct sling for this model of rifle. Additionally there are two Turkish canvas bandoleers that are in excellent condition. Each holds 70 rounds of ammo and each comes with 14 original brass 5 round stripper clips. I shot the ammo which is why it's not included.   

Price is a firm $350 with pickup in the Brandon area. This rifle is a true antique according to ATF guidelines however since it is still fully functional buyer must be at least 18 years old.   

Thanks for looking
